## 3ï¸âƒ£ What are your **mistakes & why they happen** âŒ

(These are **very important** for interviews)

---

### âŒ Mistake 1: Comparing String with `!=`

```java
if (strArr[i] != " ")
```

ğŸ”´ **Wrong**
In Java, strings are compared using `.equals()`

âœ… Correct:

```java
if (!strArr[i].equals(""))
```

ğŸ“Œ **Interview point**

> `==` compares reference, not content

---

### âŒ Mistake 2: Initializing strings with extra spaces

```java
String ans = " ";
String st = " ";
```

This adds **unwanted spaces** in output.

âœ… Should be:

```java
String ans = "";
String st = "";
```

---

### âŒ Mistake 3: Stack condition is wrong

```java
while (st.isEmpty()) {
    ans = ans + st.pop();
}
```

ğŸ”´ This loop will **never execute**

âœ… Correct:

```java
while (!st.isEmpty()) {
    ans = ans + st.pop();
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Interview trick question:

> Difference between `isEmpty()` and `!isEmpty()`

---

### âŒ Mistake 4: Comparing `char` with `" "` (String)

```java
if (ch != " ")
```

ğŸ”´ `ch` is `char`, `" "` is `String`

âœ… Correct:

```java
if (ch != ' ')
```

---

### âŒ Mistake 5: Extra space added every loop

```java
ans += " ";
```

This causes **extra spaces in output**

---

## 4ï¸âƒ£ Corrected & Clean Code âœ…

### ğŸ”¹ Approach 1: Without Stack (Best for interviews)

```java
public class ReverseStrWord {

    static void reverseString(String str) {
        String[] words = str.split(" ");
        String ans = "";

        for (String word : words) {
            String rev = "";
            for (int i = word.length() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
                rev += word.charAt(i);
            }
            ans += rev + " ";
        }

        System.out.println(ans.trim());
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = "My name is Rahul";
        reverseString(str);
    }
}
```

### âœ… Output

```
yM eman si luhaR
```

---

### ğŸ”¹ Approach 2: Using Stack (Data Structure based)

```java
import java.util.Stack;

public class ReverseStrWord {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String str = "My name is Rahul";
        Stack<Character> stack = new Stack<>();
        String ans = "";

        for (int i = 0; i < str.length(); i++) {
            char ch = str.charAt(i);

            if (ch != ' ') {
                stack.push(ch);
            } else {
                while (!stack.isEmpty()) {
                    ans += stack.pop();
                }
                ans += " ";
            }
        }

        // For last word
        while (!stack.isEmpty()) {
            ans += stack.pop();
        }

        System.out.println(ans);
    }
}
```

---

## 5ï¸âƒ£ How to explain this in an interview ğŸ§ 

> â€œI solved the problem of reversing each word in a string using two approaches.
> In the first approach, I split the string by spaces and reversed each word using a loop.
> In the second approach, I used a stack to reverse characters until a space is found, which follows the LIFO principle.
> Both approaches have O(n) time complexity.â€

